{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>SIL (also called STIL/TAL1 interrupting locus) is an immediate-early gene that is essential for embryonic development and is implicated in T-cell leukemia-associated translocations [[cite:PUB00053803], [cite:PUB00060066]]. Sil protein is necessary for proper mitotic spindle organisation in zebrafish and human cells and localizes to the mitotic spindle poles only during metaphase [[cite:PUB00060062]]. Mouse Sil was suggested to play a role as a positive regulator of the sonic hedgehog pathway, acting downstream of PTCH1 [[cite:PUB00060063]]. In human, cell cycle-dependent phosphorylation of Sil is required for its interaction with Pin1, a regulator of mitosis [[cite:PUB00060086]].</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Primary microcephaly (MCPH) is an autosomal-recessive congenital disorder characterised by smaller-than-normal brain size and mental retardation. Three different homozygous mutations in SIL were identified in patients from three of the five families linked to the MCPH7 locus; all are predicted to truncate the Sil protein [[cite:PUB00060064]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"pfam" {"PF15253" "SCL-interrupting locus protein N-terminus"}, "panther" {"PTHR15128" "TAL1 SCL INTERRUPTING LOCUS"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "SCL-interrupting locus protein", "short" "Sil"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 4, "domain_architectures" 21, "proteomes" 791, "taxa" 2940, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 2024, "sets" 0, "proteins" 1704, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 1052}, "pathways" 0}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {}, :set-info nil, :accession "IPR026123", :literature {"PUB00053803" {"URL" nil, "issue" "2", "authors" ["Golling G" "Amsterdam A" "Sun Z" "Antonelli M" "Maldonado E" "Chen W" "Burgess S" "Haldi M" "Artzt K" "Farrington S" "Lin SY" "Nissen 